===Differential diagnosis=== {{further|Differential diagnosis}}
The most common causes of drug induced acute confusion are [[dopaminergic]] drugs (used for the treatment of [[Parkinson's disease]]), [[diuretics]], [[tricyclic antidepressants|tricyclic]] or [[tetracyclic antidepressants]] and [[benzodiazepines]]. The elderly, and especially those with pre-existing dementia, are most at risk for drug induced acute confusional states.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Hufschmidt |first1=A. |last2=Shabarin |first2=V. |last3=Zimmer |first3=T. |title=Drug-induced confusional states: the usual suspects? |journal=[[Acta Neurologica Scandinavica]] |volume=120 |issue=6 |pages=436–8 |date=Dec 2009 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0404.2009.01174.x |pmid=19804475}}</ref> New research is finding a link between [[Vitamin D]] deficiency and [[cognitive impairment]] (which includes 'foggy brain').<ref>[http://www.thirdage.com/brain-fitness/vitamin-d-linked-to-cognitive-impairment''Vitamin D Linked to Cognitive Impairment'']; [[Third Age]] online; accessed: .</ref>{{Better source|reason=WP:MEDRS|date=June 2018}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018}}
