The '''Festival of Neglected Romantic Music''' was founded by musicologist [[Frank Cooper (musicologist)|Frank Cooper]] at [[Butler University]] in Indianapolis, Indiana in 1968.

==History==

Cooper directed the Festival for the next eleven years, during which time many seminal works of the Romantic era that had not been heard since the 19th century received their first modern performances, including:

*orchestral works by [[Alfred Bruneau|Bruneau]], [[Félicien-César David|David]], [[Henri Duparc (composer)|Duparc]], [[Alexander Goedicke|Goedicke]], [[Ernest Guiraud|Guiraud]], [[Józef Hofmann|Hofmann]], [[Giuseppe Martucci|Martucci]], [[Joachim Raff|Raff]], [[Anton Rubinstein]], [[Ernest Schelling|Schelling]], [[Christian Sinding|Sinding]], and [[Louis Spohr|Spohr]]; 
*concertos by [[Léon Boëllmann|Boëllmann]], [[Hans Bronsart von Schellendorff|Bronsart]], [[Alexander Dreyschock|Dreyschock]], [[Heinrich Wilhelm Ernst|Ernst]], [[Benjamin Godard|Godard]], [[Georg Goltermann|Goltermann]], [[Adolf von Henselt|Henselt]], [[Henri Herz|Herz]], [[Johann Nepomuk Hummel|Hummel]], [[Joseph Joachim|Joachim]], [[Moritz Moszkowski|Moszkowski]], [[Selim Palmgren|Palmgren]], [[Josef Rheinberger|Rheinberger]], [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov|Rimsky-Korsakov]] and [[Anton Rubinstein]]; 
*choral works by [[Niels Gade|Gade]], [[Gabriel Pierné|Pierne]], [[Joachim Raff|Raff]], [[Max Reger|Reger]], [[Giovanni Sgambati|Sgambati]] and [[Carl Maria von Weber|Weber]], 
*fully staged ballets by [[Johann Friedrich Franz Burgmüller|Burgmüller]], [[Riccardo Drigo|Drigo]], [[Alexander Glazunov|Glazunov]], [[Johann Wilhelm Hertel|Hertel]], [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]] and [[Ambroise Thomas|Thomas]], 
*solo and chamber works by [[Charles-Valentin Alkan|Alkan]], [[Felix Blumenfeld|Blumenfeld]], [[Hans Bronsart von Schellendorff|Bronsart]], [[Ernő Dohnányi|Dohnanyi]], [[Leopold Godowsky|Godowsky]], [[Eduard Nápravník|Nápravník]], [[Xaver Scharwenka]], and [[Sigismond Thalberg|Thalberg]].

Certain specific performers became associated with the Festival, including violinist [[Aaron Rosand]], pianists [[Jorge Bolet]], [[Malcolm Frager]], [[Gunnar Johansen]] and [[Raymond Lewenthal]], cellists [[James Kreger]] and [[Jascha Silberstein]], and conductors [[Victor Borge]], [[Igor Buketoff]], [[Jorge Mester]] and [[Izler Solomon]] – many of whom went on to record several of these works for commercial record labels.  Schonberg wrote many articles crediting Cooper with almost single-handedly jumpstarting the [[Romantic Revival]] in music.  The Festival continued after Cooper left.

==Reviews==
''[[The New York Times]]''' music critic [[Harold C. Schonberg]] and other critics commented on the high professional level of the presentations.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}

