{{infobox building | name = Hospicio Cabañas | image = Hospicio cabanas 1.jpg | caption = Chapel of Hospicio Cabañas | location = [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]] | coordinates = {{coord|20|40|36.74|N|103|20|16.31|W|type:landmark_region:MX-JAL|display=inline,title}} | architect = [[Manuel Tolsá]] | height = Chapel dome: {{convert|32.5|m|ft}} | floor_count = 1 | embedded = {{designation list | embed=yes | designation1 = WHS | designation1_offname = Hospicio Cabañas, Guadalajara | designation1_date = 1997 <small>(21st [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small> | designation1_type = Cultural | designation1_criteria = i, ii, iii, iv | designation1_number = [http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/815 815] | designation1_free1name = State Party | designation1_free1value = Mexico | designation1_free2name = Region | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Americas|Latin America and the Caribbean]] }} }}
The '''Hospicio Cabañas''' in [[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]], a [[World Heritage Site]], is one of the oldest and largest hospital complexes in the [[Americas]].
The complex was founded in 1791 by the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|Bishop of Guadalajara]] in order to combine the functions of a [[workhouse]], [[hospital]], [[orphanage]], and [[almshouse]]. It owes its name to [[Juan Ruiz de Cabañas]] who was appointed to the [[Episcopal see|see]] of Guadalajara in 1796 and engaged [[Manuel Tolsá]], a renowned architect from [[Mexico City]], to design the structure.
Tolsá's design was based on classic examples such as [[Les Invalides]] in [[Paris]] and [[El Escorial]] near [[Madrid]]. The buildings form a rectangle measuring {{convert|164|by|145|m}}. These are single-storey structures which are {{convert|7.5|m}} in height. The chapel is twice as high and has a dome rising to {{convert|32.5|m}}. The complex is erected on one level, "so as to facilitate the movement of the sick, the aged, and children."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://whc.unesco.org/document/154350 | title =World Hertitage List, Guadalajara, Mexico, No. 815 | last = | first = | date =1 July 1997 | website=unesco.org | publisher =[[UNESCO]] | access-date =10 December 2016 | quote = }}</ref>
[[File:Orozco hombre de fuego GDL.JPG|thumb|left|Hombre de Fuego (Man of Fire)]]
Following the death of Cabañas in 1823, construction continued until 1829. Although it served for a time as barracks in the mid-19th century, the hospital lasted well into the 20th century and continued to function until 1980, when the Cabañas Cultural Institute, with affiliated schools for arts and crafts, moved in. The highlight of the interior decoration is a series of monumental frescoes by [[José Clemente Orozco]], including one of his most famed creations, the allegory of ''The Man of Fire'' (1936–39).
Hospicio Cabaña was made a [[World Heritage Site|Unesco World Heritage site]] in 1997.<ref name="Rojas">{{cite news |last=Rojas |first=Laurie |title=French artist's site-specific interventions unveiled in Guadalajara's World Heritage Site |newspaper=[[The Art Newspaper]] |location= |pages= |language= |publisher= |date=19 March 2014 |url=http://www.theartnewspaper.com/articles/Daniel-Buren-transforms-former-hospice-in-Mexico-into-a-maze-of-colour/32084 |dead-url=yes |access-date=10 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403063824/http://www.theartnewspaper.com/articles/Daniel-Buren-transforms-former-hospice-in-Mexico-into-a-maze-of-colour/32084 |archivedate=3 April 2014 |df= }}</ref> Funded through a collaboration by the Cabañas Institute, Jalisco’s cultural ministry and the Hilario Galguera Gallery in 2014, French conceptual artist [[Daniel Buren]] created a series of site-specific works in 18 of the 23 courtyards, with cloister columns wrapped in geometric patterns, vaults painted in bright hues and mirrored structures built to create distorted views of familiar surroundings.<ref name="Rojas" />
