{{Infobox recurring event |name = Renaissance Pleasure Faire of Southern California |image = Renaissance Pleasure Faire of Southern California.jpg |alt = |caption = Renaissance Pleasure Faire of Southern California, April 2011 |location = [[Irwindale, California|Irwindale]], [[California]] |genre = Renaissance faire |first = 1962 |dates = April - May |attendance = 250,000 (average) |free_label = Stages |free_text = 11 |website = {{url|http://www.renfair.com/socal/}} }} The '''Renaissance Pleasure Faire of Southern California''' (RPFS) is the first modern [[Renaissance fair]]e to occur in America. It opened in the spring of 1963 and has been an annual event since then.<ref>{{cite book |first= Richard J. |last= Sneed |title= The Faire: Photographs and History of the Renaissance Pleasure Faire from 1963 onwards |publisher= [[The Good Book Press]] |location= Santa Cruz, CA |year= 1987 |oclc= 26491008}}</ref> Presently owned by Renaissance Entertainment Productions (REP), it is a commercial [[Historical reenactment|reenactment]] of a 1580s<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.renfaire.com/RPFI/index.html | title = REC California Faire Specifics |website= renfaire.com | accessdate = 2008-05-10}}</ref> market faire at [[Deptford|Port Deptford]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.renfair.com/socal/thefaire/entertainment.asp | title = Entertainment 2013 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130517233551/http://www.renfair.com/socal/thefaire/entertainment.asp |archivedate= 2013-05-17 |website= renfair.com | accessdate = 2013-05-13}}</ref> a waterfront town in [[Elizabethan England]]. The Faire is generally open from the first weekend of April through the weekend before Memorial Day.
==History==
Created by Ron Patterson and Phyllis Patterson, the radio station [[KPFK]], <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qmAs_DjQNP0 | title = Fairest Of the Faire}}</ref> and the nonprofit organization Living History Center (LHC),<ref name= "History"/> the first Renaissance Pleasure Faire of [[Southern California]] (RPFS) was first staged at [[Agoura Hills]] in the spring of 1963. The first Renaissance Pleasure Faire of [[Northern California]] (RPFN) occurred in the fall of 1967.
In 1989, RPFS was moved to the Glen Helen Regional Park in [[Devore, California]]; then to its present location, the [[Santa Fe Dam Recreation Area]] in [[Irwindale, California]]. In 1999, RPFN was moved to the Nut Tree in [[Vacaville, California]] and later was relocated again to [[Casa de Fruta]] in the Hollister/Gilroy area south of [[San Jose, California|San Jose]].
In 1993 RPFS was purchased by Renaissance Entertainment Corp (REC), a for-profit corporation; and later by its current owners, Renaissance Entertainment Productions (REP) (also a for-profit corporation), under whom the Faire has become more family-oriented.<ref name= "History">{{cite web | url = http://www.renfaire.com/RPFI/history.html | title = RPFI California Faire History | accessdate = 2008-05-10 |website= renfaire.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://media.www.elpaisanonewspaper.com/media/storage/paper1088/news/2007/05/16/Lifestyles/Renaissance.Pleasure.Faire.Is.For.Young.And.Old-2904409.shtml | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081202135646/http://media.www.elpaisanonewspaper.com/media/storage/paper1088/news/2007/05/16/Lifestyles/Renaissance.Pleasure.Faire.Is.For.Young.And.Old-2904409.shtml | dead-url = yes | archive-date = 2008-12-02 | title = Renaissance Pleasure Faire is for young and old | newspaper = El Paisano | location = Whittier, CA | publisher = [[Rio Hondo College]] | first = E. | last = Talavera | date = 2007-05-16 | accessdate = 2008-05-10 | department = Lifestyles | df = }}</ref>
==Attire== The costumes worn by RPFS's actors are styled after those of the period of [[Elizabeth I]] (1558-1603) and must pass a rigorous approval process ensuring their authenticity. There are five general classes of attire: [[Yeoman]], Merchant, Gentry, [[Nobility]] and Military. Other cultures represented include Scots, Italians, Germans, Spaniards, and various Arabian cultures. There are also performance groups such as [[peddler|mongers]], [[Puritan]]s, [[adventurer]]s and [[inventor]]s, which are organized into [[guild]]s. Visitors, commonly known as patrons, are encouraged to wear Renaissance-inspired costumes, but are not required to adhere to the Elizabethan period.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/ci_8741170 | title = Come play at the Faire | first = Michelle J. | last = Mills | date = 2008-03-29 | accessdate = 2008-05-10 | newspaper = [[Pasadena Star-News]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080624175010/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/ci_8741170 |archivedate= 2008-06-24}}</ref>
